<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-315-013  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 315 013.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DG Review  Jan 1989 v9 n7 p52(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Automated training in the automated office.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smith, Barry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In the changeover to automated office operations, staff trainingcan also be automated.andP;  Packages including audio, video, andcomputer-based training are now widely available.andP;  Options foremployees who are more comfortable in a traditional classroominclude running a separate lecture class or combining lectures andautomated training.andP;  One-on-one training or at least start-upsessions may also be more effective for some individuals.andO;Automated training can take up to 30 percent less time thantraditional classes, but determining whether the time comes fromlunch hours and coffee breaks or normal work hours, and how muchextra work that will amount to later, needs to be addressed inopen discussions with the entire staff.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Office AutomationTraining of EmployeesInstructional DesignComputer-Assisted Instruction.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>